In evaluting turn.js for my project, it quickly became apparent that it did not 'work' with jQueryMobile.  I seems that another user found this out a while ago, but gave up on the tool.  I decided to dig into the issue and found the main problem:

All of the 'pages' (outer DIVs) of a book are supposed to have a class of 'page-wrapper'.  However, with jQueryMobile (jQM) in the mix, they all end up getting a class of 'page-wrapper  ui-page ui-body-c'.  Those extra classes result in pages 'disappearing', and thus ruining the books.

I could not debug this, but either Emmanuel is putting in his class value first, and jQM is appending their classes afterwards, or, jQM is setting their classes to the DIVs and Emmanuel is prepending his class afterwards.  I suspect the former.

In any case, I have two pieces of code that seem to make things good.  These are 'work-arounds', and not necessarily solutions that Emmanuel might offer:
1. In the 'document ready' event, add the following line of code AFTER you 'construct' your book:
   $('div.page-wrapper').attr('class','page-wrapper');

That line essentially re-sets the class of all 'page-wrapper' DIVs to simply 'page-wrapper' (thus erasing the two extra classe the jQM added).
1.  For books with more than 6 pages, bind an event handler for the book that watches for DIVs with the page-wrapper class being added to the DOM:

   $(document).on("DOMNodeInserted", "#flipbook > div.page-wrapper", function(event){
       setTimeout("$('#flipbook > div.page-wrapper').attr('class','page-wrapper')",100);
   });

That code essentially re-sets the class value for each object that Emmanuel injects or re-injects into the DOM (remember, for books with more than 6 pages, he removes and re-adds pages as the user flips between them).  My 'selector' includes the ID of the book.  If you have only one book on your page, you do not need to worry about that.  I will have more than one and thus do not want to query or touch objects that are not changing.  I tried multiple ways to reset the class values, especially using the incoming 'event' object (and its 'target' attribute) however none seemed to work very well.  On the whole, my approach is not the most efficient, but is not terribly poor either.  But again, I have asked Emmanuel to investigate and respond.

Please let me know what you all think.

